WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.930 --> 00:00:06.300
College in America: it's four years
of all nighters, keg stands, ethnically

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:10.980
diverse welcome brochures, Pinterest
perfect dorm rooms and crushing

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:12.414
student debt.

00:00:12.420 --> 00:00:20.749
I have $69,812, $47,000, 
$90,000, $35,000, $350,000,

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:26.070
$60,000 worth of student loans. My
minimum student loan payment is $1,000

00:00:26.070 --> 00:00:26.633
a month.

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:31.470
It should take me about 10 years to
pay that back, I will be roughly 36,

00:00:31.470 --> 00:00:35.760
45-years-old, I don't know how old I'll
be when I pay that off. I was

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:44.179
actually on campus at Penn State and I
saw that I had so much to pay and

00:00:44.190 --> 00:00:47.130
it just was overwhelming. I didn't know how
to do it, I never saw a number

00:00:47.130 --> 00:00:52.560
that big. I just went to school for
a few months found out that it was not

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:57.418
what I wanted at all, and now
I have this forty thousand extra dollars

00:00:57.420 --> 00:01:02.596
that I have to pay and nothing really
to show for it. If I wasn't paying

00:01:02.610 --> 00:01:06.810
this student debt, oh my God, I would
just invest all of my money. It feels

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:10.290
like I will have a roommate for the
rest of my life because my debt is so

00:01:10.290 --> 00:01:15.360
much. You can't point at someone
and say, this person made your student

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:21.690
debt load so much more, it's the
whole system. So why is college so

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:30.470
expensive, and is it worth it? Higher
education today is made up of three

00:01:30.470 --> 00:01:34.820
main sectors. They all bring in money
from tuition but where they get the

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:37.242
rest of their revenue varies.

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:41.630
Public schools are your state schools
like SUNY or Iowa state. They get

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:45.800
money from the government. Private
for-profit schools like the University

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:50.510
of Phoenix or Capella University
get money from shareholders. And private

00:01:50.510 --> 00:01:54.770
non-profits are those like Yale an
American University, they get a lot of

00:01:54.770 --> 00:01:59.988
their money from donors. More on
that later. But choosing a college hasn't

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:06.602
always been so complicated. In
1636, America's first college was founded.

00:02:06.620 --> 00:02:10.088
You might have heard
of it before, Harvard University

00:02:10.100 --> 00:02:14.750
For hundreds of years college in America
was a pretty exclusive club to get

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:19.670
into. But we've come a long
way from Harvard's first graduating class of

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:26.120
just nine men in 1642. In
2018 more than three million Americans were

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:28.568
expected to receive a college degree.

00:02:28.580 --> 00:02:32.180
The demographics of American
higher education have been utterly

00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:33.014
transformed.

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:38.360
In 1944 the G.I. bill was signed
into law giving veterans money to attend

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:38.846
school.

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:42.399
The G.I. Bill of Rights looks
after the money end too. That's right.

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:46.845
Tuition is taken care of. Funds
are provided for laboratory fees, books,

00:02:46.850 --> 00:02:48.543
supplies and equipment are included.

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:52.640
Just a few years later, nearly
half of Americans enrolled in college were

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:53.839
veterans.

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:59.000
You cannot underestimate the G.I.
Bill. This educated an entire generation

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.550
of men and some women too. And
it opened the doors people who hadn't even

00:03:04.550 --> 00:03:09.350
thought that they might go to
college. The G.I. Bill changed what American

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:11.044
families could aspire to.

00:03:11.060 --> 00:03:16.040
But not everyone was able to take
full advantage of the bill's benefits. It

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:19.970
was significantly harder for women and
people of color to get the tuition

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:23.690
money and enroll in college
because of the widespread discrimination by

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:26.305
both schools and banks.

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:29.545
Dateline Russia 1957.

00:03:29.550 --> 00:03:33.902
In a moment the story. In the
50s a little beach ball sized satellite

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:38.570
launched into space by the Soviet Union
had a big impact on the American

00:03:38.570 --> 00:03:40.002
education system.

00:03:40.010 --> 00:03:45.080
The first Sputnik. People were worried
about this clash between the Soviet

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:49.610
Union and the United States. And
suddenly it was popular to study science

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:51.599
and math. It was patriotic.

00:03:51.620 --> 00:03:56.135
In the 60s the civil rights movement
helped push the doors open even wider

00:03:56.150 --> 00:04:00.800
to give women and people of
color access to higher education. In those

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:04.400
years students at University of
California schools paid less than a

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:08.648
thousand dollars in registration fees. No
tuition if you were a resident.

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:11.888
But with the 70s
came the taxpayer revolt.

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:17.452
If you want something you pay for it.
Don't expect me to pay for it. It's

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:24.638
your problem not mine. And so
what happened was the student loan process

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:29.331
exploded. And then came the
U.S. News and World Report.

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:35.855
It was one of the luckiest
or most ingenious publishing decisions ever.

00:04:35.900 --> 00:04:41.120
In 1983 U.S. News and World
Report published a list of America's Best

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:48.278
Colleges. It became a highly data
driven ranking. Every one of the

00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:53.330
criteria that U.S. News used
depended on name recognition, traditional

00:04:53.330 --> 00:04:57.752
quality, prestige and most of all
wealth. Rankings played a big thing for

00:04:57.770 --> 00:04:58.070
me.

00:04:58.065 --> 00:05:00.925
I was an athlete and
so I was pretty competitive.

00:05:00.950 --> 00:05:06.890
There have been a ton of new lists
since the 1983 ranking but the U.S. News

00:05:06.890 --> 00:05:11.900
and World Report still reigns king.
And colleges keep a pretty close eye

00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:12.290
on it.

00:05:12.276 --> 00:05:17.420
If you ask them they will say they
pay no attention to it. But within the

00:05:17.416 --> 00:05:20.810
conference rooms of the admissions
office and provost offices across the

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:25.370
land, I can assure you they
pay very close attention to it.

00:05:25.325 --> 00:05:30.620
One thing they're paying attention to
are their test score averages. By the

00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:35.270
90s, colleges started boosting base tuition
and using the extra money to

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:39.560
give merit based scholarships to kids
who tested well. The chief data

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:44.240
strategist at U.S. News and World
Report downplayed test scores as a major

00:05:44.240 --> 00:05:48.140
factor in their ranking, saying it's
less than eight percent of the

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:52.190
methodology today. And that "We've
seen schools perform best in the

00:05:52.190 --> 00:05:56.390
rankings if they emphasize and
perform strongly in student outcome areas

00:05:56.384 --> 00:06:01.040
like graduation and retention rates.
He also said they further decrease

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:06.710
the weight of SAT and ACT scores.
Tuition costs at both public and private

00:06:06.710 --> 00:06:10.520
colleges have doubled since the late
80s, even when you account for

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:16.010
inflation. Even so, more Americans
are getting college degrees. But state

00:06:16.010 --> 00:06:21.980
funding for public universities has taken
a hit. States spent less on

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:27.980
higher education in 2017 than they
did in 2008 before the recession. And

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:32.450
that means students are spending more.
The tuition they're paying is a big

00:06:32.450 --> 00:06:37.790
moneymaker for colleges. 2017 was the
first year ever that most state

00:06:37.790 --> 00:06:41.660
schools got more money from tuition
than they did from government funding.

00:06:41.654 --> 00:06:44.600
If you're sitting in the state
legislature and you're looking for money,

00:06:44.558 --> 00:06:48.750
the university system is one of
your biggest costs. So when you realize

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:51.230
well we cut them 2 percent last
year, they didn't go out of business.

00:06:51.217 --> 00:06:55.640
Let's cut them another 2 percent. What
happens is you pass the buck. It

00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:59.030
goes from the
taxpayer to the student.

00:06:58.993 --> 00:07:04.040
The average student graduates with
about $37,000 in student debt

00:07:03.998 --> 00:07:08.300
altogether. The U.S. has
$1.5 trillion dollars of it.

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:20.570
I had this mindset that I was gonna
go to college undergrad and then I was

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:24.600
gonna go to grad school and get my
PhD. I thought that I would get through

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:29.430
it and then come out on the other side
with a job and then be able to pay

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:32.777
it off. But that did
not go according to plan.

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:37.080
Rachel Brandt got her undergraduate degrees
in math and economics from Iowa

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:42.162
State. Then she moved to New
York to pursue her master's in economics.

