I thought that I would just withdraw
and be fine. But then a couple of

00:07:51.630 --> 00:07:55.170
weeks after I withdrew, I got an
email from the school saying that I owed

00:07:55.170 --> 00:08:01.290
them $6,000 right away. And that was
rough. So I didn't know how I was

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:03.344
going to pay that.
And that was very stressful.

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:12.040
Three, four, five, six,

00:08:12.014 --> 00:08:18.460
seven different student loans that all
have to be paid with different

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:19.790
interest rates.

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:28.147
The number just keeps going up. I
will be paying $867 in rent a month

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:34.540
and that's about how much I'm going to
have to be paying in loans. I look

00:08:34.540 --> 00:08:38.425
at my bank account every
day and it's very scary.

00:08:38.470 --> 00:08:43.090
Rachel is far from the only one
not to finish a degree she started. Only

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:48.660
about 57 percent of undergrads complete
their degree within six years. One

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:52.680
option students turn to for a
more flexible and at times more affordable

00:08:52.680 --> 00:08:57.630
path to a degree are for-profit
colleges like University of Phoenix or

00:08:57.630 --> 00:09:04.110
DeVry University. The industry has been
in flux, but today a little more

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:09.707
than 900,000 students attend for-profit colleges
in the U.S., many of whom

00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:12.165
use federal loans to
help cover the cost.

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:16.170
I feel like I want to do
something practical that would that would clearly

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:20.520
lead to a specific job. The Art
Institute of New York City was suggested

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:26.490
to me. Now, I really regret that it
was because it turned out to be a

00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:28.700
terrible financial experience.

00:09:28.710 --> 00:09:32.760
Despite for-profits being just a small
fraction of all colleges in the

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:37.290
U.S., for-profit students default on their
student debt at a much higher

00:09:37.290 --> 00:09:38.576
rate.

