test it out. In New York
City, Governor Cuomo implemented a program that

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:57.210
gives middle-class residents free tuition
at select state schools. And

00:16:57.210 --> 00:17:00.600
some billionaires like Bill Gates are
giving their own money to try and

00:17:00.600 --> 00:17:05.328
fix the system. And of course
there's the idea to offer free college.

00:17:05.370 --> 00:17:09.540
I do not agree with free college.
I think that when you give someone

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:14.220
something for free they do not realize
the value of it, and that's just my

00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:18.467
opinion, and I think that there
should be some cost associated with it.

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:24.480
Free college is a great idea. I
am fully supportive of free college. The

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:27.047
catch is: who's going
to pay the bill?

00:17:27.060 --> 00:17:31.440
In other countries taxpayers foot most
of the bill. So instead of paying

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:35.940
student loans later in life, you're
paying higher taxes. Roughly two dozen

00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:39.720
countries across the world provide free
or almost free college to its

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:40.945
citizens.

00:17:40.980 --> 00:17:45.240
The solution probably won't be that
simple in the U.S. But with student

00:17:45.240 --> 00:17:49.020
debt rising and the need for
a college degree becoming more and more

00:17:49.020 --> 00:17:53.670
important, the future of American
education depends on figuring this out.

